  "Since the p-value (0.012) is less than alpha (0.05), we reject H0. There is statistically significant evidence that the mean ER wait time differs from 45 minutes.": "",
  "A researcher tests a new fertilizer and gets a p-value of 0.048. She reports 'The fertilizer significantly increased crop yield (p = 0.048).' Her colleague points out that at alpha = 0.01, the result would not be significant. What does this illustrate about hypothesis testing?": "",
  "The test is invalid because two people disagree": "",
  "Alpha = 0.01 is always the correct choice": "",
  "The result is only significant at more lenient alpha levels; the choice of alpha matters and should be set before the study": "",
  "The result is always significant regardless of alpha": "",
  "This illustrates that significance depends on the chosen alpha level. A result with p = 0.048 is significant at alpha = 0.05 but not at alpha = 0.01. The significance level should be determined before data analysis.": "",
  "A website runs an A/B test comparing two homepage designs. Design B gets a 2.1% higher click-through rate than Design A. With 50,000 visitors per group, the p-value is 0.001. A manager asks: 'Is a 2.1% difference practically important, or just statistically significant?' What is the best answer?": "",
  "With very large samples, even tiny differences become statistically significant; the practical importance of a 2.1% difference depends on business context": "",
  "Statistical significance and practical significance are always the same": "",
  "Statistical significance guarantees practical importance": "",
  "The result is not significant because 2.1% is too small": "",
  "With very large samples, even tiny real differences produce very small p-values. Statistical significance means the effect is real, but the 2.1% difference may or may not be worth acting on depending on costs and revenue impact.": "",
  "A school district claims the dropout rate is 8%. A concerned parent group surveys 300 students and finds that 30 dropped out (10%). They conduct a one-tailed test with Ha: p > 0.08 and find z = 1.27 with p-value = 0.102. At alpha = 0.05, what is the conclusion, and what might the parent group do next?": "",
  "Reject H0 because the sample rate (10%) is higher than 8%": "",
  "Reject H0 because z = 1.27 is positive": "",
  "Fail to reject H0; the difference is not statistically significant, but the group might consider a larger sample to increase power": "",
  "Accept H0 and conclude the dropout rate is exactly 8%": "",
  "Since p-value (0.102) > alpha (0.05), we fail to reject H0. The 10% sample rate is not significantly higher than 8%. The group could collect a larger sample to increase statistical power to detect a real difference if one exists.": ""
